  "method": "Context-Aware Cascade Reranking (CARE) augments a standard dense retriever with a lightweight, query-conditioned reranking pipeline that never re-encodes the full corpus. Offline, each document is enriched once with: (i) k multi-view embeddings (viewer tokens) that capture diverse facets of the same text and remain ANN-compatible; (ii) a compact, LLM-written synopsis that emphasizes claims, constraints, entities, and temporal qualifiers, which is then embedded; and (iii) optional token-level embeddings or sub-vector shards stored in a late-interaction index to enable query-only re-encoding. We also extract a small set of structured facets (entities, dates, locations, stance) to build a sparse feature sketch per document.\n\nAt query time, we derive the missing context the dense retriever ignores. A frozen LLM rewrites the current query (plus session history if available) into a short intent-and-constraint description that teases out skills, operations, entities, and boundary conditions (e.g., \"compare methods A vs B after 2021, prioritize causal evidence\"). We encode this description into a context vector, and we also parse out weighted facets (entities, time windows, polarity) for explicit matching. A first-stage ANN search over the base dense index returns top-N candidates.\n\nCARE then applies a three-pass cascade over only these N candidates. Pass A (cheap, vector-only) re-scores with max/aggregate similarity between the query’s context vector and each document’s k viewer vectors plus its synopsis embedding, and adds explicit facet-overlap bonuses (e.g., Jaccard on entities, time-window compatibility). This removes superficially similar but context-mismatched items and prunes to M candidates. Pass B (late interaction) encodes the query tokens once and computes MaxSim-style interactions against precomputed document token embeddings to capture subtle phrasings, negations, and attribute bindings, pruning to L. Pass C (neural listwise) presents the residual L candidates to a small LLM reranker using single-token decoding of an ordinal relevance label or a direct permutation head; the model judges nuanced contextual fit from short snippets and produces the final order without expensive multi-token generation.\n\nFor continuous improvement without corpus re-encoding, CARE distills the LLM’s listwise ordering into the query embedding with a weighted RankNet objective over the already-retrieved candidates, and (optionally) issues a second ANN query using the updated vector to recover any missed but highly contextual results. All heavy document-side computations were done offline; online work is confined to query rewriting, query-only encodings, sparse facet lookups, and scoring a few dozen candidates.",
  "rationale": "Dense retrievers compress documents into single vectors, which fails when fine-grained constraints (e.g., dates, stance, attribute bindings) determine relevance. CARE injects these contextual signals in three complementary ways while avoiding any corpus-wide re-encoding: (1) intent/skill rewriting improves the query representation to target operations and constraints, (2) multi-view document embeddings and synopsis vectors expose diverse facets for better ANN-friendly matching, and (3) a late-interaction step and a compact listwise LLM reranker resolve the remaining hard cases with minimal additional latency. Because all document-side features are precomputed once, the online cost scales only with top-N candidates, not corpus size.\n\nThe cascade is designed to be cost-aware: cheap vector re-scoring and explicit facet checks quickly fix most mis-rankings; late interaction with query-only encoding captures subtle token-level alignments without reprocessing documents; and a single-token listwise LLM pass delivers robust judgments on the final shortlist. Finally, distilling the LLM’s ordering into the query vector provides immediate, session-level gains in recall and ranking without touching the corpus encodings.",
