  "method": "Use a two-stage reranking cascade on the dense retriever’s top-K without touching the corpus index. First, freeze the dense retriever and keep its precomputed passage embeddings. At query time, fetch top-K via ANN and form a feature vector per candidate that combines: (a) the frozen dense similarity (dot/cosine) between the query and passage embeddings; (b) lightweight lexical signals computed on-the-fly over the candidate (BM25/tf-idf overlap, phrase/NE overlap, proximity); and (c) cheap structured matches from pre-extracted passage metadata (entities, dates, sections, authority/source). Optionally, select up to B evidence sentences per candidate by a fast sentence-level BM25 or MaxSim over token embeddings and run a tiny cross-encoder or late-interaction scorer only on those snippets to produce an evidence-alignment score. Concatenate these signals into a pointwise base score S(d|q) for each candidate.\n\nTrain a small pairwise preference head g(q, di, dj) that operates on frozen embeddings and the above features only. Concretely, g takes [q-emb || di-emb || dj-emb || Δlex || Δstruct || Δevidence] and outputs P(di ≻ dj | q). This can be implemented as a linear probe or shallow MLP; it never re-encodes documents and is trained from click/pairwise labels or supervised pairs. Because it consumes frozen vectors and cheap deltas, it is fast and data-efficient while being sensitive to subtle, context-dependent cues captured by the auxiliary features and evidence snippets.\n\nAt inference, apply an efficient adjacent-swap reranking on the top-K using g. Initialize with the dense order, then perform m right-to-left passes over the top-k window (k ≤ K): compare only adjacent items (i, i+1) with g and swap if P(di+1 ≻ di | q) > 0.5. Repeat for a small m (e.g., 1–3) until stable. This yields O(m·k) pairwise calls instead of O(K^2), captures non-linear pairwise preferences induced by contextual signals, and corrects many dense-order mistakes with minimal latency. Cache per-candidate features so each pairwise call is just a cheap concatenation and an MLP/linear pass.\n\nDeploy with guardrails: calibrate g with temperature scaling, blend the final score as S*(d|q) = S(d|q) + λ·LocalRank(d) to preserve coarse relevance, and fall back to pointwise S for very large K. Maintain a small, periodically refreshed metadata store (entities, timestamps) alongside the dense index so contextual features remain up to date without re-embedding passages.",
  "rationale": "Dense retrievers excel at topical recall but miss fine-grained, query-dependent cues. The proposed reranker injects those cues as lightweight lexical, structural, and snippet-level evidence computed only for the retrieved top-K, avoiding any corpus-wide re-encoding. A frozen-embedding pairwise head learns preferences di ≻ dj conditioned on the query, leveraging precomputed vectors and cheap deltas to be sensitive to subtle context without incurring cross-encoder costs over the whole document set.\n\nUsing an adjacent-swap schedule concentrates pairwise comparisons where they matter (near the top) and achieves strong reorderings with O(K) complexity per pass, making the method practical under tight latency budgets. Training the pairwise head as a linear/shallow probe over frozen embeddings further reduces cost while empirically retaining much of the necessary discriminative power, yielding an efficient, context-aware reranker that complements dense retrieval.",
