  "method": "We propose CONCERT: Context-Conditioned Evidence Routing for Reranking. Offline, each corpus document is segmented into sentences. For every sentence we store: (a) a frozen dense embedding from the base retriever backbone, (b) a sparse lexical signature (n-grams, entities), and (c) lightweight IE triples (subject, relation, object) with IDs and types. No query-time re-encoding of corpus text is required; only these cached per-sentence representations and metadata are used.\n\nAt query time, we form a compact context vector g by encoding the current query, conversational history, and optional user/task metadata. A tiny facetizer (rules + a small LLM) decomposes the query into facets (entities, relations, temporal/numeric constraints, polarity), each with a frozen embedding. Given the top-N dense-retrieved documents, we build a Contextual Evidence Graph (CEG) over the candidate set: facet nodes on one side and candidate evidence nodes (the l highest-scoring sentences per document found via ANN over cached sentence embeddings against each facet) on the other. Edges carry multi-view alignment features: dense similarity, lexical/entity overlap, triple compatibility, temporal/numeric agreement, and simple contradiction cues. A lightweight linear probe maps these frozen features to an edge support score s_ij, while a prototype-based head produces a calibration/confidence u_ij. We run 1–2 rounds of message passing on the CEG where attention weights are modulated by the global context g; evidence nodes aggregate messages from covered facets and return coverage/consistency signals, yielding a per-document state h_d that summarizes which facets are supported and where conflicts arise.\n\nWe then perform Active Glimpse Refinement under a fixed budget B. Using the current CEG, we compute a value-of-information score that combines (i) edge influence on the document’s objective (via the message-passing Jacobian) and (ii) uncertainty u_ij. The top-B edges (facet–sentence pairs) are re-examined with a tiny cross-encoder or constrained pattern matcher over just the sentence and facet text (never the full document). Each refined edge updates s_ij, and we incrementally update the document states h_d through a discretely-online evidence integrator that smoothly incorporates new signals without re-running the full propagation.\n\nFinally, we score each document with a context-faithful coverage objective: a soft-AND over critical facets plus weighted soft-OR over optional facets, minus penalties for contradiction (e.g., polarity or temporal mismatch) derived from the CEG. To ensure that improvements stem from contextual matching rather than topical proximity, we add a counterfactual sensitivity term: for each critical facet, we efficiently re-evaluate the document’s score with that facet masked using cached message-passing factors; documents whose scores do not decrease under facet removal are down-weighted. We sort candidates by the resulting score. This produces a context-aware reranking that uses precomputed sentence-level caches and only a handful of on-the-fly micro-glimpses, never re-encoding the corpus.\n",
  "rationale": "Dense retrieval is strong at topical alignment but weak when subtle constraints (temporal, numeric, polarity, multi-entity relations) govern relevance. CONCERT explicitly models those constraints by factorizing the query into facets and routing evidence between facets and sentence-level caches within a per-query micro-graph. Global context g modulates edge attention so session/user signals shift which facets and evidence matter, while the counterfactual sensitivity term rewards candidates whose relevance truly depends on the specified context rather than surface similarity.\n\nCrucially, all heavy lifting is done over frozen, offline-computed sentence embeddings and light IE triples; at query time we only run graph computations and a budgeted number of micro cross-encodes on select facet–sentence pairs. The discretely-online integrator lets us incorporate these refinements incrementally without rebuilding scores from scratch, and the prototype-driven uncertainty head ensures we spend that compute where it is most impactful. Together, this yields reranking that is context-faithful and compute-efficient without re-encoding the corpus.\n",
